  "When x = a, the integral from a to a of f(t) dt = 0 by the zero-width property. So every accumulation function starts at zero when x equals the lower limit.": "",
  "What does 'concavity of an accumulation function' tell us about the integrand?": "",
  "Concavity is unrelated to the integrand": "",
  "Concavity tells us the sign of the integrand": "",
  "If F is concave up, the integrand is negative": "",
  "If F is concave up, then f (the integrand) is increasing; if concave down, f is decreasing": "",
  "Since F'(x) = f(x), we have F''(x) = f'(x). F is concave up when F''(x) = f'(x) > 0, meaning f is increasing. F is concave down when f'(x) < 0, meaning f is decreasing.": "",
  "What is the 'chain rule version' of FTC Part 1?": "",
